Parents,

As required by the Texas Education Agency, Fort Elliott CISD will provide an online school option for the 2020-2021 school year. For planning purposes, we are asking parents to fill out the google form to determine how many students in grades 3-12 will be interested in the online option. Our school district prefers to provide in-person instruction for our students, but we understand the current environment. Thank you for your time. https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfz3CSx24aZSsTPXLTpS9XGv3Y2FAsIz5w9JBQXvNjsjQYifA/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text:
To: Ft. Elliott parents

I wanted to let all parents know how Ft. Elliott CISD is handling the school closure due to the Corona virus.

Instructional packets will be delivered to Ft. Elliott students in PK-5 that ride a bus beginning Tuesday morning, March 24th. Parents of students that do not ride a bus can pickup the packets at the High School office beginning on Tuesday, March 24th after 9 am. Instructional packets will be available on a weekly basis while Ft. Elliott is out of school.
Students in grades 6-12 will be provided online instruction through their individual teachers.

Lunches will be made available to students beginning Tuesday, March 24th. Lunches will be consist of snack packs that will be good for a week. The snack packs will be available at the High School office and at the Fellowship hall at the First Baptist church in Mobeetie from 11 till 1 on Tuesday through Thursday. The snack packs will be free of charge to all students. One bag per child, per week.

The Ft. Elliott CISD offices will be open from 8 till 3 on Monday-Thursday.

Frank Belcher, Superintendent

post_text:
Ft. Elliott CISD will not have school the week of March 23-27. Teachers and staff will meet Monday to plan for alternative instruction. Packets will be delivered to PK-5 students homes on Tuesday. Students in grades 6-12 will need to check school email for assignments from their teachers.. Students are encouraged to continue to practice recommended social distancing and safe hygiene practices in order to prevent the spread of this virus.

Ft. Elliott is committed to the safety and health of our students and staff and will continue to monitor the situation week by week.

Mr. Belcher
Superintendent

post_text:
Ft. Elliott CISD is aware of the current Coronavirus situation. Ft. Elliott CISD receives frequent guidance and updates from the Texas Department of Health Services, as well as, the Texas Education Agency. We will continue to monitor the situation and take preventative measures to ensure the health of our students. The District is taking extra steps to ensure our classrooms and facilities are clean and safe.

Ft. Elliott CISD, with the guidance of the Texas Department of Health Services will plan for alternative methods of providing instruction after Spring break as the situation warrants.

I hope everyone has a great Spring break.

Frank Belcher, Superintendent

Post-Secondary Readiness

Sharon Winward Davis
May 7, 2019 at 3:25 PM ·

We have no right to EVER question the potential of God's people!
We think we know someone & based on their past performance, we lock them in to an expected behavior.
We all struggled at some point, so we must honor other's struggles too!
It's the job of a leader to STAY OPEN to the future potential of others!
Good stuff!
#thebrendonshow

post_text: This beautiful baby quilt was made for baby Jax James by Fort Elliott Kindergarten class and their awesome sub, Mrs. Dyck. Mrs. Dyck is pictured with the finished quilt and Mrs. James is pictured with her Kindergarten class accepting their gift of love for baby Jax. The quilt features the handprint and name of each student in Mrs. James' Kindergarten class. Mrs. Dyck asked each student what they wanted added to their handprint to make a special picture for baby Jax. Mrs. Dyck completed the pictures and the quilt.

post_text: Sonya Holder was presented a painting from the Fort Elliott CISD Board of trustees and a money tree from the Fort Elliott Faculty and Staff in appreciation of her years of service to Briscoe/Fort Elliott from 1981-2017. Ms. Holder started her teaching career at Briscoe in 1981 and has been a great asset to this school district throughout her career. We would like to wish Ms. Holder the very best of luck in your retirement. You will be missed by your coworkers and students, as well as the Fort Elliott community.

post_text:
Saturday, February 20, 2016, two students from Fort Elliott CISD represented their school in the Region I UIL Vocal Solo Contest at Canyon, TX. Caitlynn Walker, junior, and Mykah Jasman, sophomore, sang vocal solos in Class 1 and Class 2, respectively. Both received Superior ratings for their performances, each bringing home a medal.

Class 1, the highest possible level of competition, is the only category in which a student can advance to state competition, and only then after receiving the highest possible rating (Superior). Having attained that rating, Caitlynn Walker will be advancing to perform in the Texas State UIL Solo Contest on Memorial Day Weekend in Pflugerville, Texas.

Both girls are to be commended for their hard work, their superior performances, and their excellent representation of their high school.

Submitted by Ariel Lohberger, Fort Elliott Music Director
